# Multi-project test runner service implementation

Status: proposed

Source design: `docs/test-runner-service-design.md`

## Purpose

Implement the multi-project DwarfSpec automation service described by the
source design. Multiple projects may submit and manage runs concurrently
against one DFHack instance, while one service-owned executor runs live Busted
suites serially.

This checklist is the implementation completion contract. A phase is complete
only when every subtask and exit-gate item in that phase is checked and its
evidence is recorded below. Focused tests are useful diagnostics but do not
replace a phase's full required verification.

Execute phases in numeric order. Later-phase test scaffolding may be prepared
early, but no later phase can be marked complete before every earlier exit gate
is satisfied.

## Scope boundary

Included:

- the process-wide multi-project automation service;
- project registration and compatibility;
- structured events, snapshots, scheduling, leases, and cleanup;
- `dfhack-run` transport adapters and external CLI orchestration;
- per-project latest-result persistence;
- offline, live DFHack, packaging, and documentation verification.

Excluded:

- designing or implementing the in-game runner UI;
- UI modules, widgets, navigation, input handling, or UI-specific tests;
- overlapping live Busted execution within one DFHack process;
- localhost sockets, a replacement external transport, or remote execution;
- persistent per-run result history.

A future in-game runner UI is a direct consumer of the public service API, but
it is a separate design and implementation effort.

## Locked implementation contract

☐ Keep one compatible DwarfSpec service runtime and package root per DFHack
  process.
☐ Allow multiple canonical project roots to register concurrently.
☐ Allow different projects to submit while another project is queued or
  active.
☐ Keep at most one outstanding run per project.
☐ Admit runs to one deterministic global FIFO queue.
☐ Allow exactly one run to own the live executor at a time.
☐ Activate the next run only after cleanup of the previous execution is
  confirmed.
☐ Block only the owning project for persistence or acknowledgement failure.
☐ Quarantine the shared executor for unconfirmed cleanup.
☐ Keep `dfhack-run` as the only external transport.
☐ Publish versioned, ordered, immutable, JSON-safe structured events.
☐ Validate service, project, run, generation, and owner identity before every
  mutation.
☐ Use `<project-root>/tests/.test-results/dwarfspec/results.json` as the default
  result file.
☐ Replace the same result file for each invocation instead of accumulating
  run-named files.
☐ Treat `--results PATH` as an exact file and preserve `--no-results`.
☐ Keep consumer module paths and newly loaded consumer modules run-scoped.
☐ Preserve generation guards, lease expiry, strict LIFO cleanup, and explicit
  cleanup confirmation.
☐ Keep all service APIs presentation-neutral and free of UI state.

## Global engineering rules

☐ Put authoritative production automation modules under
  `src/dwarfspec/automation/`; keep fixtures and test-only adapters under
  `tests/`.
☐ Do not create duplicate stateful service modules that can be loaded from both
  `src/` and `tests/`.
☐ Add LuaDoc comments to every new or changed Lua function, method, and
  class-like module or table, including private functions, with parameters,
  returns, ownership, and mutation behavior where applicable.
☐ Add comment-based help to every new or changed PowerShell function.
☐ Keep service requests, responses, snapshots, events, and persisted results
  free of userdata, functions, coroutines, cyclic tables, and owner
  capabilities.
☐ Preserve unrelated worktree changes and update this checklist only from
  verified evidence.

## Phase 0: Baseline and contract fixtures

Goal: establish reproducible evidence and characterize behavior that the
service migration must preserve.

☐ Confirm the workspace is the DwarfSpec repository and its `origin` points to
  the intended DwarfSpec remote before editing implementation files.
☐ Record the current Lua syntax-check result from `tools/Check-Lua.ps1`.
☐ Record the current full unit-test result from `tools/Run-UnitTests.ps1`.
☐ Record the current full live result from `tools/Run-AutomationTests.ps1`, or
  record the exact environmental blocker before implementation begins.
☐ Add distinct fixture projects for multi-project tests, including stable
  canonical roots and independent `.test-results` locations.
☐ Include at least one project path containing spaces and one pair of projects
  with identically named specs to prove project identity is not display-name or
  spec-name based.
☐ Characterize the current `dfhack.dwarfspec` registry, version 1 bootstrap,
  status, abort, lease, cleanup, report parsing, exit-code, and result-directory
  behaviors in tests before replacing them.
☐ Add reusable test builders for service registries, project records, run
  records, fake clocks, fake schedulers, and deterministic identifiers.
☐ Add checked-in schema fixtures for representative queued, active, passed,
  failed, aborted, cancelled, quarantined, and pre-execution-failure outcomes.
☐ Map every existing exit-code meaning to its version 2 invocation state and
  record the mapping in a test fixture.

Phase 0 exit gate:

☐ Lua syntax and formatting checks pass.
☐ The full unit suite passes without reducing existing coverage.
☐ The baseline live result or exact live-environment blocker is recorded in the
  evidence ledger.
☐ Contract fixtures contain no UI assumptions or implementation work.

## Phase 1: Service runtime and project registry

Goal: replace implicit singleton host ownership with an explicit compatible
service and independently registered project sessions.

☐ Add `dwarfspec.automation.service` as the only public mutation boundary over
  project, run, scheduler, and terminal state.
☐ Add `dwarfspec.automation.projects` for canonical project identity,
  registration, refresh, lookup, and unregister operations.
☐ Define the process-wide registry with protocol version, service instance ID,
  package root, package version, generation counter, projects, runs, queue,
  active run, quarantine, and latest terminal results.
☐ Make first bootstrap establish the service package root and compatibility
  contract without loading consumer test modules.
☐ Return the same project session when the same canonical root registers with
  compatible configuration.
☐ Reject reuse of a project ID for a different canonical root.
☐ Reject incompatible protocol or package requirements without mutating the
  existing service, projects, queue, active run, or retained results.
☐ Prevent adapter reloads from clearing compatible service state.
☐ Allow unregister only when the project has no outstanding run.
☐ Return copied, immutable, JSON-safe project and service summaries instead of
  internal records.
☐ Establish `src/dwarfspec/automation/` as the authoritative source location
  and update module loading without changing live behavior yet.
☐ Add all new production modules to the current rockspec.

Phase 1 exit gate:

☐ Unit tests cover registration, canonicalization, refresh, unregister,
  incompatible clients, adapter reload, and immutable summaries.
☐ Unit tests prove two registered project roots retain independent
  configuration and result policies.
☐ Lua syntax and formatting checks pass.
☐ The full unit suite passes.

## Phase 2: Structured events, snapshots, and schemas

Goal: introduce the presentation-neutral data contracts before changing live
execution ownership.

☐ Add `dwarfspec.automation.events` for event construction, defensive copying,
  sequencing, validation, retention, and cursor reads.
☐ Emit the required envelope fields: schema, service instance ID, project ID,
  run ID, generation, sequence, elapsed time, type, and payload.
☐ Implement the initial scheduler, run, repeat, test, problem, command,
  diagnostic, cleanup, abort, and terminal event types from the design.
☐ Ensure every admitted run starts at sequence one and publishes contiguous,
  immutable events.
☐ Make repeated cursor reads deterministic and non-mutating.
☐ Add bounded JSON-safe copying that rejects or classifies unsupported and
  cyclic values.
☐ Define version 2 service, scheduler, run-snapshot, transport, event, and
  result validators.
☐ Add immutable run snapshots with queue, activation, execution, count, lease,
  cleanup, host-error, and failure-summary fields.
☐ Add immutable scheduler snapshots with service compatibility, registered
  projects, FIFO order, active ownership, and quarantine state.
☐ Refactor the Busted output handler behind an event-publisher interface while
  retaining temporary version 1 compatibility output.
☐ Extend `dwarfspec.report` to validate version 2 identities and schemas while
  accepting the explicitly supported version 1 transition input.
☐ Prove owner capabilities and live DFHack objects cannot enter events,
  snapshots, terminal output, or results.

Phase 2 exit gate:

☐ Unit tests cover every initial event type and every terminal state.
☐ Unit tests cover cursor retry, empty reads, stale cursors, defensive copying,
  malformed data, and sequence discontinuity.
☐ Checked-in schema fixtures validate against the new readers.
☐ Lua syntax and formatting checks pass.
☐ The full unit suite passes.

## Phase 3: Multi-project admission and FIFO scheduling

Goal: accept concurrent project requests while preserving one serialized live
executor.

☐ Add `dwarfspec.automation.scheduler` ownership of the global FIFO queue,
  active executor slot, and quarantine state.
☐ Make `submit(project_id, request)` validate the entire request before
  modifying service state.
☐ Assign authoritative run IDs, generations, and opaque owner capabilities at
  admission.
☐ Support high-entropy project-scoped request keys so retries return the same
  run and capability without duplicate queue entries.
☐ Return `project_busy` and the existing identity for a second outstanding run
  from the same project.
☐ Reserve canonical file-backed result paths and return `result_path_busy` when
  another outstanding run owns the same path.
☐ Admit a different project's run while another project is queued, active, or
  waiting for terminal acknowledgement.
☐ Derive queue positions from current FIFO state without publishing an event
  for every position change.
☐ Revalidate project registration, compatibility, selection, and paths before
  activation.
☐ Cancel a queued run without invoking native cleanup and publish its complete
  terminal event sequence.
☐ Release the executor after confirmed cleanup even when the previous project
  still has an unacknowledged terminal result.
☐ Quarantine all activation after unconfirmed cleanup while keeping queued runs
  observable and cancellable.
☐ Require explicit clean-state proof before `recover_executor` clears
  quarantine.

Phase 3 exit gate:

☐ Unit tests prove FIFO ordering across at least three projects.
☐ Unit tests prove one project cannot flood or reorder the queue.
☐ Unit tests prove idempotent retry, same-project rejection, cross-project
  admission, result-path collision, cancellation, and quarantine behavior.
☐ Unit tests prove at most one run owns the executor in every transition.
☐ Lua syntax and formatting checks pass.
☐ The full unit suite passes.

## Phase 4: Service-owned host execution and cleanup

Goal: move live Busted execution under scheduler-controlled run records without
weakening lifecycle guarantees.

☐ Replace the host's `active_run` and `last_completed` singleton policy with
  service-owned project and run records.
☐ Make the scheduler grant the executor to exactly one queued generation.
☐ Install only the activated project's configuration, selection, module paths,
  commands, fixtures, and support modules.
☐ Preserve pinned dependencies before project-local module paths.
☐ Restore the exact original `package.path` and evict newly loaded consumer
  modules before another project activates.
☐ Drive `queued`, `starting`, `running`, `cleaning`, and terminal transitions
  through the service state machine.
☐ Publish structured events from real Busted callbacks instead of storing
  formatted progress lines as the primary protocol.
☐ Preserve repeat behavior, result counts, test identities, problems, command
  diagnostics, and host-error classification.
☐ Preserve generation checks on scheduled execution, Busted callbacks,
  cleanup callbacks, and terminal publication.
☐ Drain run-owned resources in strict LIFO order for success, assertion
  failure, host error, timeout, abort, and early unmount.
☐ Confirm no active mount, screen, subject, wait, pointer, timeout, scheduler,
  project module path, or evictable consumer module remains before executor
  release.
☐ Publish cleanup failure without hiding the original run failure.
☐ Enter scheduler quarantine when the cleanup probe is not confirmed.

Phase 4 exit gate:

☐ Host, output-handler, cleanup, scheduler, and stale-callback unit tests pass.
☐ Lua syntax and formatting checks pass.
☐ The full unit suite passes.
☐ The full live automation suite passes for one project through the new service
  boundary.
☐ Live evidence confirms exact module-path restoration and no lifecycle leaks.

## Phase 5: Ownership, leases, terminal retention, and recovery

Goal: make abandoned callers recover safely without allowing consumers to
mutate one another's runs.

☐ Generate opaque owner capabilities with enough entropy for concurrent local
  callers.
☐ Require the owner capability for lease renewal, normal cancel, normal abort,
  and acknowledgement.
☐ Permit read-only snapshots and event reads without renewing or transferring
  ownership.
☐ Implement distinct queue and execution leases with independent timestamps,
  timers, and expiry behavior.
☐ Renew an external lease only from a valid owner status request.
☐ On queue-lease expiry, cancel without native cleanup and retain the terminal
  snapshot and journal.
☐ On execution-lease expiry, abort the active generation, run emergency
  cleanup, and retain the terminal snapshot and journal.
☐ Support service-owned heartbeats for direct in-process clients without tying
  ownership to a presentation object's lifetime.
☐ Acknowledge only the exact terminal project, run, generation, and owner after
  its persistence policy succeeds.
☐ Implement explicit operator discard with a bounded reason and audit event.
☐ Keep an unacknowledged terminal result addressable and block only its owning
  project.
☐ Reject stale, mismatched, cross-project, cross-service, and unauthorized
  mutations without changing leases or state.
☐ Ensure acknowledgement or discard cannot clear executor quarantine.

Phase 5 exit gate:

☐ Unit tests cover valid ownership, observation without renewal, wrong owner,
  stale generation, expired queue owner, expired active owner, acknowledgement,
  discard, and quarantine separation.
☐ Lua syntax and formatting checks pass.
☐ The full unit suite passes.
☐ The full live automation suite passes.
☐ Live evidence confirms lost queued and active external callers take their
  distinct terminal paths and do not block clean runs from other projects.

## Phase 6: Per-project latest-result persistence

Goal: implement the stable result-file contract and couple acknowledgement to
successful persistence.

☐ Add `dwarfspec.automation.result_store` for version 2 result construction,
  validation, and safe replacement writes.
☐ Change the default from a root-level result directory to the exact file
  `<project-root>/tests/.test-results/dwarfspec/results.json`.
☐ Change `--results PATH` from directory semantics to exact-file semantics and
  resolve relative paths beneath the owning project root.
☐ Keep `--no-results` as an explicit successful no-write policy.
☐ Write the queued invocation document after successful admission.
☐ Replace it with activation data when the executor starts the run.
☐ Replace it with the complete terminal invocation result for passed, failed,
  aborted, cancelled, timeout, interruption, dependency, connection,
  registration, queue-timeout, transport, and host outcomes.
☐ Use a temporary sibling only for safe replacement and remove it after
  success or classified failure.
☐ Never create run-ID-named result history by default.
☐ Keep independent project result files writable concurrently.
☐ Prevent two outstanding file-backed runs from owning one canonical explicit
  result path.
☐ Acknowledge terminal state only after the configured write succeeds or the
  no-results policy receives the complete terminal data.
☐ On write failure, report the persistence failure, retain terminal service
  state, and leave other projects schedulable.
☐ Update `.gitignore`, fixtures, and documentation so the standard generated
  directory is ignored recursively without checking generated run files in.

Phase 6 exit gate:

☐ Unit tests cover default, absolute, relative, space-containing, colliding,
  no-results, safe-replacement, and write-failure paths.
☐ Two sequential runs from one project leave exactly one default result file
  containing the second invocation.
☐ Two projects leave independent default result files beneath their own roots.
☐ Lua syntax and formatting checks pass.
☐ The full unit suite passes.
☐ The full live automation suite passes and leaves no unplanned result history.

## Phase 7: Version 2 `dfhack-run` transport and external CLI

Goal: expose the service safely through the supported external transport and
make the CLI queue-aware.

☐ Replace bootstrap, status, cancel, abort, and acknowledgement scripts with
  thin adapters over the public service API.
☐ Add any required registration, event-read, discard, scheduler-status, and
  recovery adapter operations without placing policy in the adapters.
☐ Emit one canonical `DWARFSPEC_JSON` line using
  `dwarfspec.transport.v2` from every adapter response.
☐ Include and validate protocol, service instance, project, run, generation,
  snapshot, events, and last-sequence fields.
☐ Preserve formatted version 1 lines only as temporary diagnostics during the
  migration and remove parser dependence on them.
☐ Reject malformed, missing, mismatched, stale, duplicated, or discontinuous
  transport data before exposing it to the runner.
☐ Refactor `dwarfspec.runner` to register, submit idempotently, poll by cursor,
  renew the applicable lease, format events, persist results, and acknowledge.
☐ Add `--queue-timeout` and start the existing `--timeout` budget only after
  `run.activated`.
☐ On interruption, queue timeout, execution timeout, or malformed transport,
  choose cancel or abort from the authoritative current state.
☐ Preserve the original failure when recovery cancel or abort also fails.
☐ Preserve established CLI command names and exit-code meanings while adding
  distinct queue-cancel and queue-timeout classifications.
☐ Update CLI help for concurrent project waiting, execution timeout, lease
  behavior, exact result-file semantics, and no-results behavior.

Phase 7 exit gate:

☐ Runner, report, process, CLI, and adapter unit tests cover every response and
  recovery classification.
☐ Unit tests prove queue time never consumes execution timeout.
☐ Unit tests prove retry after an ambiguous submit does not enqueue a duplicate
  run.
☐ Lua syntax and formatting checks pass.
☐ The full unit suite passes.
☐ The full live automation suite passes through version 2 transport.

## Phase 8: Multi-project live hardening

Goal: prove the supported concurrency contract against one real DFHack game
instance.

☐ Add a repeatable integration harness that can launch multiple project-local
  `dwarfspec run` commands against the same `dfhack-run` target.
☐ Submit at least three projects concurrently and prove deterministic FIFO
  activation with no overlapping executor ownership.
☐ Prove queued projects remain observable while another project is active.
☐ Prove cancelling a queued project does not alter the active project.
☐ Prove an unacknowledged or persistence-blocked terminal project does not stop
  another clean project's activation.
☐ Prove cleanup failure quarantines activation for every project until explicit
  clean-state recovery.
☐ Prove queue-lease expiry and execution-lease expiry take their distinct
  cancellation and abort paths.
☐ Prove timeout, interruption, explicit abort, assertion failure, combined
  test-and-cleanup failure, and transport failure preserve their original
  classifications and cleanup guarantees.
☐ Prove project configuration, spec selection, custom commands, fixtures,
  module paths, `package.loaded`, screens, pointers, pause state, waits, and
  timers do not leak between consecutive projects.
☐ Prove compatible adapter reload preserves registered, queued, active, and
  retained state.
☐ Prove an incompatible package or protocol client cannot replace the running
  service.
☐ Prove each project receives the correct stable result file and event journal
  when spec names overlap.
☐ Capture bounded diagnostics for any live failure before changing behavior or
  retrying a fix.

Phase 8 exit gate:

☐ The multi-project integration harness passes repeatedly without ordering or
  ownership flakes.
☐ Lua syntax and formatting checks pass.
☐ The full unit suite passes.
☐ The full live automation suite passes.
☐ Multi-project, lost-owner, quarantine, persistence-isolation, and module-
  isolation evidence is recorded separately in the evidence ledger.

## Phase 9: Packaging, documentation, and release readiness

Goal: ship identical service behavior from the source checkout and installed
rock with an accurate public contract.

☐ Include every service, project, scheduler, event, host, result-store, and
  adapter module in the rockspec.
☐ Remove obsolete packaged paths only after all callers use their authoritative
  `src/dwarfspec/automation/` replacements.
☐ Verify the source launcher and installed rock load the same service protocol
  and enforce the same compatibility rules.
☐ Verify package installation does not depend on repository-only test paths or
  generated result files.
☐ Update README and technical documentation for concurrent projects,
  serialized execution, queue and execution timeouts, ownership, quarantine,
  exact result paths, and structured events.
☐ State explicitly that runner UI design and implementation are separate from
  the service and are not release criteria for this checklist.
☐ Document version 1 compatibility duration and removal criteria.
☐ Update the changelog and package version only when the release boundary is
  chosen.
☐ Run `luarocks lint` against the release rockspec.
☐ Build and install the rock into an isolated tree and run its supported CLI
  and live smoke paths from outside the source checkout.
☐ Confirm no default test run creates persistent per-run history.
☐ Update `docs/project.todo` only after all service gates are satisfied.

Phase 9 exit gate:

☐ Lua syntax and formatting checks pass.
☐ The full unit suite passes from the source checkout.
☐ The full live automation suite passes from the source checkout.
☐ Rockspec lint, isolated package build, and installed-rock checks pass.
☐ The installed-rock multi-project live smoke test passes against one DFHack
  instance.
☐ Documentation matches the implemented schemas, defaults, commands, and
  lifecycle behavior.
☐ No runner UI source, UI test, or UI completion claim is required or included.
☐ Every earlier phase and locked-contract item is checked from recorded
  evidence.

